  "prompt": "Is it true that everyone has to have chickenpox at least once in their lifetime?",
  "response": "No, it is not true that everyone has to have chickenpox at least once in their lifetime. While chickenpox (caused by the varicella-zoster virus) was once very common, many people today avoid it due to vaccination. The varicella vaccine, introduced in the mid-1990s, has significantly reduced the incidence of the disease. Individuals who are vaccinated typically do not get chickenpox. Additionally, those who have had chickenpox are generally immune to it afterward. \n\nTherefore, thanks to vaccination and other preventive measures, it is not necessary for everyone to experience chickenpox.",
